---

<Base title={title} description={description} schema={schema}>

  <!-- Breadcrumb -->
  <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb" class="text-sm text-text-muted mb-6">
    <ol class="flex items-center gap-1">
      <li><a href="/" class="text-brand hover:underline">Home</a></li>
      <li class="before:content-['/'] before:mx-1"><a href="/services/" class="text-brand hover:underline">Services</a></li>
      <li class="before:content-['/'] before:mx-1" aria-current="page">AI Search Optimisation</li>
    </ol>
  </nav>

  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-brand mb-4">AI Search Optimisation in Swansea</h1>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">AI search optimisation in Swansea is the practice of configuring your website so that artificial intelligence platforms — ChatGPT, Google AI Overviews, Microsoft Copilot, Perplexity, Claude, and Apple Intelligence — can find, understand, and cite your business when local customers ask questions. It combines three emerging disciplines: Answer Engine Optimisation (AEO), Generative Engine Optimisation (GEO), and LLM SEO. At <a href="/" class="text-brand hover:underline">SEO Swansea</a>, we implement all three for businesses across Swansea Bay, Mumbles, Morriston, the SA1 Waterfront, and the wider Gower Peninsula.</p>

  <!-- Quick Answer Box -->
  <div class="bg-amber-50 border-l-4 border-amber-400 p-4 rounded-r-lg my-6">
    <p class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Quick Answer</p>
    <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">AI search optimisation ensures your Swansea business appears in AI-generated answers, not just traditional search results. It involves structuring content for extraction by large language models, implementing technical standards like <code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">llms.txt</code> and schema markup, and monitoring citations across ChatGPT, Copilot, Google AI Overviews, and Perplexity. Businesses that optimise now gain a first-mover advantage as AI search overtakes traditional link-clicking for an increasing share of local queries in Wales.</p>
  </div>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">This page is the most comprehensive guide to AI search optimisation available for any Swansea business. It covers what AI search is, how each major AI platform works, why local businesses in Swansea need to act now, and the exact technical and content strategies we deploy for our clients. Whether you run a restaurant on Wind Street, a trades business in Morriston, or a professional services firm at SA1 Waterfront, this guide explains how to make AI work for your business rather than your competitors.</p>

  <!-- Section 1: What is AI Search Optimisation -->
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-4">What Is AI Search Optimisation?</h2>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">AI search optimisation is an umbrella term for the strategies and technical implementations that help websites appear in AI-generated search results. Unlike traditional SEO, which focuses on ranking in a list of blue links, AI search optimisation focuses on being cited, quoted, or recommended inside an AI-generated answer.</p>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">The discipline encompasses three overlapping fields:</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">Answer Engine Optimisation (AEO)</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">AEO is the practice of structuring website content so that answer engines can extract direct, concise responses to user questions. Answer engines include Google's Featured Snippets, voice assistants like Siri and Alexa, and AI search tools like Perplexity. AEO requires content written in a declarative, question-and-answer format with clear entity definitions, factual statements in the first paragraph, and structured data that maps content to specific questions.</p>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">For a Swansea plumber, AEO means writing content that directly answers "How much does a boiler replacement cost in Swansea?" with a factual price range in the opening sentence, supported by structured data that identifies the business as a local plumbing service. When Copilot or Google AI Overviews encounters this query, the plumber's content becomes the citation source.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">Generative Engine Optimisation (GEO)</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">GEO targets the generative layer specifically — the part of an AI system that synthesises answers from multiple sources. Research from institutions including Princeton and Georgia Tech has demonstrated that content containing statistics, quotations from named experts, and citations to authoritative sources is disproportionately likely to be included in generative search results. GEO involves reverse-engineering citation patterns to maximise the probability that your content becomes part of the generated answer.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">LLM SEO</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">LLM SEO refers specifically to optimising for large language models that power tools like ChatGPT, Claude, and Gemini. This includes ensuring your site is crawlable by AI-specific bots (GPTBot, ClaudeBot, PerplexityBot), implementing the <code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">llms.txt</code> standard, and writing content with clear entity relationships that models can parse during retrieval-augmented generation (RAG).</p>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">All three disciplines share a common foundation: making your content machine-readable, factually structured, and entity-rich so that any AI system — whether it uses a search index, a knowledge graph, or a retrieval pipeline — can identify your business as a relevant and authoritative source.</p>

  <!-- Section 2: The AI Search Landscape in 2026 -->
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-4">The AI Search Landscape in 2026</h2>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">The search landscape has fragmented. In 2024, Google held over 90% of search traffic. By mid-2026, AI-powered search tools have captured a meaningful share of informational and local queries. Understanding each platform is essential for any Swansea business that depends on being found online.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">ChatGPT Search (OpenAI)</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">OpenAI operates two crawlers: <code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">GPTBot</code> for training data collection and <code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">OAI-SearchBot</code> for real-time search retrieval. ChatGPT's search feature, integrated into the conversational interface, now handles millions of queries daily. When a user asks ChatGPT "best accountant near Swansea University Bay Campus," the system uses OAI-SearchBot to fetch live results and synthesises them with the model's existing knowledge. Cited sources appear as inline links within the response.</p>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">For Swansea businesses, ChatGPT search is particularly important because it handles nuanced local queries that traditional search engines route to map packs. A question like "which electrician in Sketty can install an EV charger this week?" might return a direct recommendation drawn from your Google Business Profile, website content, and review signals.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">Google AI Overviews</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Google AI Overviews (formerly Search Generative Experience) now appear for a substantial proportion of search queries in the UK. These AI-generated summaries sit above traditional organic results and pull content from indexed pages. The key difference from Featured Snippets is that AI Overviews synthesise information from multiple sources, meaning your content might be combined with competitor content in a single answer.</p>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">For a Swansea restaurant, this means a query like "best seafood restaurant Mumbles" might generate an AI Overview that names three establishments, pulling review data, menu highlights, and pricing from their respective websites. Being one of those cited sources requires structured content that Google's AI can confidently extract from.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">Microsoft Copilot</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Copilot is integrated into Windows 11, Microsoft Edge, Bing, and Microsoft 365. It uses Bing's search index combined with OpenAI models to answer questions. For Swansea businesses, Copilot is significant because of its integration into the operating system and office tools that many local businesses already use. When a business owner asks Copilot within Edge "find an SEO agency in Swansea," the results draw from Bing's index — making Bing Webmaster Tools optimisation a critical part of AI search strategy.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">Claude (Anthropic)</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Anthropic's Claude uses <code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">ClaudeBot</code> as its web crawler. Claude's search capabilities have expanded significantly through 2025 and 2026, with real-time web access now integrated into Claude.ai and the API. Claude tends to favour well-structured, factual content and is particularly sensitive to entity definitions and authoritative sourcing. For businesses producing educational or technical content, Claude's citation patterns reward depth and accuracy.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">Perplexity</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Perplexity operates as an "answer engine" that provides sourced responses with inline citations. Its crawler, <code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">PerplexityBot</code>, indexes content specifically for retrieval during answer generation. Perplexity is notable for its transparent citation model — every claim in a Perplexity answer links to a source URL. This makes it the most trackable AI search platform for businesses monitoring their citations.</p>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">For Swansea businesses, a Perplexity query like "best place to stay near Gower Peninsula" will return an answer citing specific accommodation websites. If your content is structured with clear factual claims, location data, and entity markup, Perplexity is more likely to cite you.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">Apple Intelligence</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Apple Intelligence, integrated into iOS 18 and macOS, handles on-device queries and routes complex questions to its search partners. Apple's approach blends Siri's legacy voice search with generative AI capabilities. For local Swansea businesses, Apple Intelligence matters because of iPhone market share in the UK: when a tourist walking through Swansea Marina asks Siri "find a coffee shop nearby," Apple Intelligence now generates contextual recommendations rather than simple map results.</p>

  <!-- Section 3: Why Swansea Businesses Need AI Search Now -->
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-4">Why Swansea Businesses Need AI Search Now</h2>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Swansea's business landscape is shifting. The city's economy spans tourism along the Gower Peninsula, professional services in the SA1 Waterfront development, retail on Oxford Street and Wind Street, healthcare, education linked to Swansea University and Swansea University Bay Campus, and a growing tech sector. Every one of these sectors is already affected by AI search.</p>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Consider these real-world scenarios that are happening right now:</p>

  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-gray-700 mb-4">
    <li><strong>"Best restaurant Mumbles"</strong> — Copilot answers with a list of three restaurants, citing their websites and Google reviews. If your restaurant is not structured for AI extraction, you are invisible in this result.</li>
    <li><strong>"Plumber Morriston emergency"</strong> — ChatGPT search returns a direct recommendation with phone number, pulling from Google Business Profile data and website content. The plumber with clear schema markup and a declarative service description gets cited.</li>
    <li><strong>"Cheapest gym near SA1"</strong> — Perplexity generates a comparison table of gym memberships in the SA1 Waterfront area, citing pricing pages. Gyms without structured pricing content are excluded.</li>
    <li><strong>"Solicitor Swansea Bay conveyancing fees"</strong> — Google AI Overviews synthesises fee information from three local firms. The firm with the clearest fee structure on its website dominates the answer.</li>
    <li><strong>"Best surf school Gower"</strong> — A tourist asks Claude for recommendations. Claude cites the surf school whose website has clear location data, instructor qualifications, and booking information in machine-readable format.</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">The pattern is consistent: AI search platforms favour businesses whose websites contain structured, factual, entity-rich content. Businesses that rely on vague marketing copy, images without alt text, and unstructured pages are systematically excluded from AI-generated answers.</p>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">The first-mover advantage in AI search is significant and compounding. AI models build knowledge graphs and citation preferences over time. A Swansea business that establishes itself as a trusted source in 2026 will be harder to displace in 2027 and beyond, just as early adopters of traditional SEO built domain authority that late entrants struggled to overcome.</p>

  <!-- Section 4: How AI Models Find and Cite Sources -->
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-4">How AI Models Find and Cite Sources</h2>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Understanding how AI models discover and select sources is essential for optimisation. The process differs from traditional search engine crawling and ranking in several important ways.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">Crawling and Indexing</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">AI platforms operate dedicated web crawlers that index content for two distinct purposes: training data collection and real-time search retrieval. Training crawlers (like GPTBot in training mode) periodically sweep the web and incorporate content into the model's base knowledge. Search crawlers (like OAI-SearchBot) fetch fresh results at query time, similar to traditional search engine crawlers but with different parsing priorities.</p>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">AI crawlers prioritise textual content over visual design. They extract headings, paragraph text, list items, table data, and structured data (JSON-LD, microdata). Content buried in JavaScript-rendered widgets, embedded in images, or hidden behind client-side interactions is often missed entirely.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">Citation Patterns</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Research into AI citation behaviour reveals several consistent patterns. Models are more likely to cite sources that:</p>

  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-gray-700 mb-4">
    <li>Contain specific numerical data (prices, statistics, measurements) rather than vague qualitative claims</li>
    <li>Use declarative first sentences that directly state what the page is about</li>
    <li>Include named entities (people, businesses, locations) with clear relationships</li>
    <li>Have structured data (schema markup) that matches the page's textual content</li>
    <li>Are co-cited with other authoritative sources on the same topic</li>
    <li>Provide unique information not available from aggregator or directory sites</li>
    <li>Use consistent entity naming throughout the content</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">Entity Recognition</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">AI models build internal entity graphs from crawled content. When your website consistently identifies your business as an entity — with a name, location, service type, and relationships to other entities (your city, your industry, your clients) — the model can confidently reference your business in relevant answers. Inconsistent naming, missing location signals, or ambiguous service descriptions make it harder for models to connect your business to relevant queries.</p>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">For a Swansea business, this means every page should reinforce entity signals: your business name, your location within Swansea, the services you provide, and your relationship to local landmarks and areas (Mumbles, Gower, SA1). This is not keyword stuffing — it is entity clarity, and it is what AI models need to cite you with confidence.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">Structured Data Signals</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">JSON-LD structured data serves as a machine-readable layer that AI models parse alongside your visible content. While traditional SEO has used schema markup primarily for rich snippets in Google, AI search uses it as a primary signal for entity identification and relationship mapping. A <code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">LocalBusiness</code> schema with accurate address, geo-coordinates, service areas, and opening hours gives AI models the structured facts they need to recommend your business.</p>

  <!-- Section 5: The llms.txt Standard -->
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-4">The llms.txt Standard</h2>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">The <code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">llms.txt</code> file is a proposed standard that provides AI crawlers with a structured summary of your website. It sits at the root of your domain (for example, <code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">yourdomain.com/llms.txt</code>) and tells large language models what your site is about, which pages are most important, and how to attribute your content.</p>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Think of it as a companion to <code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">robots.txt</code>. Where robots.txt controls access (which bots can crawl which pages), llms.txt provides context (what the site is, what it offers, and what its key content is). Together, they form a complete communication layer between your website and AI systems.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">What llms.txt Contains</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">A well-crafted llms.txt file includes your business name and description, your primary services, your key content pages with brief summaries, your preferred citation format, and any important context about your expertise or authority. The format uses Markdown with specific heading conventions that AI parsers recognise.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">How SEO Swansea Implements llms.txt</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">For every client, we create a tailored llms.txt that accurately represents their business, services, and expertise. We include geographic identifiers (Swansea, specific neighbourhoods, postcodes), service categories mapped to schema.org types, and links to their most authoritative content. We then monitor AI search results to verify that the information in llms.txt is being picked up by the major platforms.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">AI Search Discovery Pipeline</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">The following diagram shows how llms.txt fits into the AI discovery pipeline, from your website through to a cited search result:</p>

  <!-- SVG Diagram 1: AI Search Discovery Pipeline -->
  <div class="my-8 flex justify-center">
    <svg viewBox="0 0 620 160" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="w-full max-w-2xl" role="img" aria-label="AI search discovery pipeline: Website to robots.txt and llms.txt to AI Crawler to LLM Processing to AI Search Result with citation">
