  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">Keywords vs Entities</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Traditional SEO revolves around keyword research — finding the phrases people type into Google and optimising pages to rank for them. AEO shifts the focus to entities: named things with properties and relationships. Instead of targeting the keyword "plumber Swansea," AEO identifies your business as an entity of type <code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">Plumber</code> located in the entity <code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">Swansea</code>, providing the service <code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">Emergency Plumbing</code>. AI models think in entities, not keywords.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">Backlinks vs Citations</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">In traditional SEO, backlinks from other websites signal authority. In AI search, citations within AI-generated answers serve a similar function. A citation is when an AI model names your business or links to your content in its response. Earning citations requires being the most structured, factual, and relevant source on a topic — not the most linked-to.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">Rankings vs Answers</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Traditional SEO measures success by position in search results: position 1 gets the most clicks, position 10 gets almost none. In AI search, there is no list of ten results. There is one generated answer that may cite one, two, or three sources. You are either in the answer or you are not. This binary outcome makes AI search optimisation higher-stakes than traditional ranking battles.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">CTR vs Brand Mentions</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Traditional SEO tracks click-through rate: the percentage of impressions that result in a website visit. In AI search, many users get their answer without clicking through to any source. The value shifts from clicks to brand mentions — being named as a trusted source builds awareness and credibility even when the user does not visit your site. For Swansea businesses, this means success is measured partly by how often AI tools recommend your brand, not just how many people click your link.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">Content Strategy Differences</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">AEO content strategy differs from traditional SEO in several practical ways. Every page should open with a declarative first paragraph that directly states what the page is about — this is the text AI models are most likely to extract. FAQ sections with <code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">FAQPage</code> schema provide pre-formatted question-answer pairs that models can extract verbatim. Comparison tables, pricing information, and step-by-step processes should use HTML tables and ordered lists rather than prose paragraphs, because AI parsers can extract structured formats more reliably.</p>

  <!-- Section 7: GEO: Generative Engine Optimisation -->
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-4">GEO: Generative Engine Optimisation</h2>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Generative Engine Optimisation is the most forward-looking branch of AI search optimisation. While AEO focuses on being extracted as a direct answer, GEO focuses on being woven into AI-generated narratives. When Google AI Overviews or ChatGPT synthesises a response from multiple sources, GEO determines whether your content makes the cut.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">How Generative Models Select Sources</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Generative models use retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) to combine their base knowledge with fresh search results. During this process, the model retrieves candidate documents, scores them for relevance and authority, extracts key claims, and synthesises them into a coherent answer. Your content needs to survive each stage of this pipeline.</p>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Research has identified several factors that increase source inclusion in generative results:</p>

  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-gray-700 mb-4">
    <li><strong>Quantitative data:</strong> Content with specific numbers, percentages, and statistics is cited 30-40% more frequently than qualitative content alone</li>
    <li><strong>Expert attribution:</strong> Quotes and statements attributed to named experts or credentialled professionals increase citation likelihood</li>
    <li><strong>Technical terminology:</strong> Using precise industry terminology signals depth and helps models match your content to specific queries</li>
    <li><strong>Recency signals:</strong> Content with dates, "updated" timestamps, and references to current events scores higher in freshness-sensitive queries</li>
    <li><strong>Co-occurrence with authority:</strong> Content that references or is referenced by other authoritative sources in the same domain benefits from co-citation patterns</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">Citation Optimisation Techniques</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">For Swansea businesses, citation optimisation means ensuring your content contains unique, verifiable claims that AI models need to attribute. A Swansea solicitor who publishes "conveyancing in Swansea typically completes in 8-12 weeks, with Land Registry fees of approximately £270 for properties under £300,000" provides the specific, citable data that AI models surface in answers. Compare this with vague copy like "we offer competitive conveyancing services" — the AI has nothing concrete to cite.</p>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">We implement GEO for our <a href="/services/" class="text-brand hover:underline">Swansea clients</a> by auditing existing content for citation potential, adding quantitative data points, structuring claims as extractable facts, and ensuring each page contains at least one unique insight that no competitor offers. This combination of depth and specificity is what separates content that gets cited from content that gets ignored.</p>

  <!-- Section 8: robots.txt for AI Crawlers -->
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-4">robots.txt for AI Crawlers</h2>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Your <code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">robots.txt</code> file controls which bots can access your website. For AI search optimisation, this file is a critical gatekeeper. If you block AI crawlers in robots.txt, your content cannot appear in AI-generated answers — it is that simple.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">AI Crawlers You Should Allow</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">The following AI crawlers should be explicitly allowed in your robots.txt if you want to appear in AI search results:</p>

  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-gray-700 mb-4">
    <li><code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">GPTBot</code> — OpenAI's general crawler (used for training and search)</li>
    <li><code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">OAI-SearchBot</code> — OpenAI's real-time search crawler (used for ChatGPT search)</li>
    <li><code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">ClaudeBot</code> — Anthropic's crawler for Claude</li>
    <li><code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">PerplexityBot</code> — Perplexity's answer engine crawler</li>
    <li><code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">Applebot-Extended</code> — Apple's extended crawler for Apple Intelligence features</li>
    <li><code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">Google-Extended</code> — Google's AI training crawler (separate from Googlebot)</li>
    <li><code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">Bytespider</code> — ByteDance's crawler (used for TikTok's search features)</li>
    <li><code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">cohere-ai</code> — Cohere's crawler for enterprise AI applications</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">How SEO Swansea Configures robots.txt</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">For our Swansea clients, we configure robots.txt to explicitly allow all beneficial AI crawlers while maintaining appropriate blocks on admin areas, staging environments, and duplicate content. We also set crawl-delay directives for aggressive bots that might impact server performance, particularly for smaller Swansea businesses on shared hosting.</p>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Many default WordPress and website builder configurations block some or all AI crawlers. This is one of the most common issues we find during our <a href="/seo-audit-swansea/" class="text-brand hover:underline">SEO audits in Swansea</a> — businesses unknowingly blocking GPTBot or ClaudeBot and wondering why they never appear in AI search results.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">The Access vs Training Decision</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Some businesses worry about allowing AI crawlers to use their content for model training. This is a legitimate concern, and the decision is yours to make. However, blocking training crawlers while allowing search crawlers (where possible) gives you the best of both worlds: your content appears in AI search results without contributing to training data. OpenAI, for example, honours robots.txt blocks on GPTBot for training while using OAI-SearchBot separately for search. We help each client make this decision based on their specific content, competitive position, and comfort level.</p>

  <!-- Section 9: Structured Data for AI -->
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-4">Structured Data for AI Search</h2>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Structured data has always been important for SEO, but for AI search it becomes essential. JSON-LD schema markup provides AI models with a machine-readable layer of information that supplements your visible content. While a human reads your paragraph about opening hours, an AI model reads your <code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">OpeningHoursSpecification</code> schema to extract the same information with perfect accuracy.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">Essential Schema Types for Swansea Businesses</h3>

  <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-700 mt-6 mb-2">LocalBusiness</h4>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Every Swansea business should implement <code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">LocalBusiness</code> schema (or a more specific subtype like <code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">Restaurant</code>, <code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">LegalService</code>, or <code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">Plumber</code>) with complete address, geo-coordinates, service area, opening hours, and contact information. This schema is the primary way AI models identify your business as a local entity. Include <code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">areaServed</code> with Swansea and your specific service areas.</p>

  <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-700 mt-6 mb-2">FAQPage</h4>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4"><code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">FAQPage</code> schema wraps your frequently asked questions in a format that AI models can extract as direct answers. When someone asks ChatGPT "how much does a haircut cost in Swansea," and your salon has a FAQ with that exact question and a specific price answer marked up with FAQPage schema, your content becomes the most extractable source. We implement FAQPage schema on every <a href="/services/" class="text-brand hover:underline">service page</a> and location page for our clients.</p>

  <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-700 mt-6 mb-2">HowTo</h4>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4"><code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">HowTo</code> schema structures step-by-step processes in a format optimised for AI extraction. A Swansea electrician who marks up "How to Request an EICR Certificate in Swansea" as a HowTo with individual steps, estimated time, and costs provides exactly the structured process data that AI models surface in procedural queries.</p>

  <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-700 mt-6 mb-2">Service with Offer</h4>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4"><code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">Service</code> schema with embedded <code class="bg-gray-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono">Offer</code> objects describes what you provide and how much it costs. This is particularly valuable for AI search because pricing queries ("how much does X cost in Swansea?") are among the most common commercial queries handled by AI assistants. Providing structured pricing data makes your business the definitive source for these answers.</p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-3">Schema Consistency</h3>

  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">A critical and often overlooked aspect of structured data for AI is consistency. Your schema must exactly match your visible content. If your schema says you are open until 6pm but your website text says 5:30pm, AI models lose confidence in your data and may not cite you at all. We audit schema-content alignment as part of every <a href="/technical-seo-swansea/" class="text-brand hover:underline">technical SEO project</a> we deliver in Swansea.</p>

